Part 1: Mapping Hospital Beds in North Carolina Counties

The U.S. Department of Homeland Security collects Homeland Infrastructure Foundation-Level Data in order to support community preparedness, resiliency, research, and more.

One of the pieces of data it collects and shares with the public is information about all the hospitals in the United States, including the number of beds and their location.

Source: https://hifld-geoplatform.opendata.arcgis.com/ Source: https://hifld-geoplatform.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/hospitals/explore?location=21.228667%2C-115.674385%2C3.62 Data Dictionary: https://hifld-geoplatform.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/geoplatform::hospitals/about

Before you download the Shapefile and get into that, go ahead and download a version thats in a file format with which youre already familiar. In this case, we see a CSV file that should open up easily in Excel or Google Sheets.

In addition to the CSV and Shapefile formats, you will see file such as KML (keyhole markup language, used for Google Maps and other stuff() and GeoJSON, which is often used for building interactive web apps.

Note that the Shapefile data we download gives us a .zip file format that we will have to decompress. When we decompress Hospitals.zip we will get a new directory/folder on our computer called Hospitals. Its inside this directory/folder that we will find our Hospitals.shp file.

Whatever you do, dont separate this Hospitals.shp from its family. It needs all the other little files Hospitals.xml, Hospitals.dbf, Hispitals.shx, Hospitals.cpg, and Hospitals.prj with it in the same directory in order for it to behave properly.

hospitals <- sf::st_read("Hospitals/Hospitals.shp")
## Reading layer `Hospitals' from data source

nc <- hospitals %>% filter(STATE == "NC")

ggplot() + geom_sf(data=nc)

#4. Use geom_sf() to make a map of the counties in North Carolina

ggplot() + geom_sf(data=ncpop)

5. Make a map of hospitals and counties.

ggplot() + geom_sf(data=ncpop) + geom_sf(data=nc) + theme_void()

The map we just made makes it easy to see that some counties have more hospitals than others. In fact, we see that some counties have no hospitals at all. But we know that some hospitals are bigger than others. And we also know that some counties have more people than others. Maybe every county has the same hospital capacity relative to its population. We might operationalize hopital capacity as total hospital beds in a county divided by total population. Lets map that

6. Join the hospital location data to the Census data.

# First, let's use the DHS data to add up the the number of beds in each county.


ncbeds <- nc %>%
  filter(BEDS > 0) %>%
  group_by(COUNTY) %>%
  summarize(county_beds = sum(BEDS)) %>%
#I suspect there's a better way to do this, but I found that select() doesn't work with sf objects. So I temporarily convert it to a "tibble," which is a "lazy and surly" type of data frame that you can read more about here: https://tibble.tidyverse.org/    
  as_tibble() %>%
  select(COUNTY, county_beds)



#Now we notice that there is no column in ncpop that contains EXACTLY the same values that are contained in the COUNTY column in ncbeds. Human minds are flexible and can see that the NAME column in ncpop is the name of the county, but inflexible computers can't figure that out. So if you asked a computer to join these two dataframes by matching the ncpop$COUNTY to ncbeds$name, the computer would be all, like, "Nope, no matches." And you'd be all, like, "Stupid computer! I can see the matches right there!"

#So here we have to help out by first making sure that the NAME column doesn't have any leading or trailing invisible white spaces, then we have to chop off the " County, North Carolina" characters, and then finally convert the proper casing to all upper case (again, because computers are REALLY inflexible and dumb). Finally, to do just one nice thing for our own human minds, we'll change the name of the NAME column to a more descriptive -- and easier to join -- COUNTY.

ncpop <- ncpop %>%
  mutate(COUNTY = str_trim(NAME)) %>%
  mutate(COUNTY = str_sub(COUNTY,1,str_length(COUNTY)-23)
         ) %>%
  mutate(COUNTY = str_to_upper(COUNTY)) 


#Then we just join. And don't even have to explicitly tell R which columns to join because we've made it perfectly clear to our hard-working but somewhat dense computer helper.

ncall <- left_join(ncpop, ncbeds,
                         # by=c("COUNTY"="COUNTY")
                   )
## Joining, by = "COUNTY"
ncall<- ncall %>%
  mutate(pop_per_bed = estimate / county_beds)

7. Map beds per person.

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data=ncall, 
          aes(fill=pop_per_bed)) + 
  theme_void()

Those gray counties indicate counties that dont have any hospitals. That might be exactly the story you want to tell. But you also might want to say, Well, I want to show how many people in each of those counties dont have a bed. I cant divide by zero. Taking the entire population might be less precise but more enlightening. Lets do that. We can use a new function called coalesce() from the tidyverse tomush together the values in the estimate column with the NA values in the pop_per_bed column. A better description of coalsce() is at https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/coalesce.html

ncall<- ncall %>%
  #mutate(pop_per_bed = estimate / county_beds) %>%
  relocate(pop_per_bed, .after = county_beds) %>%
  mutate(pop_per_bed = coalesce(pop_per_bed, estimate))

8. Add the following information to our map:

A title that says 16 Counties Have People, But No Hospital A caption that says Source: US Census, Department of Homeland Security A title for the legend that says People Per Bed Make the counties that have more people per bed darker than the counties that have fewer people per bed.

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data=ncall, aes(fill=pop_per_bed)) + 
  scale_fill_distiller(direction=1, name="People Per Bed") +
  labs(title="16 Counties Have People, But No Hospital", caption="Source: US Census, Department of Homeland Security") + 
  theme_void()

Time for a little break

Tidycensus will give you acess to a lot of Census data, but not everything. If you want access to the ENTIRE Census API via R, the best tool is the censusapi package created by journalist Hannah Recht: https://www.hrecht.com/censusapi/articles/getting-started.html

When you install tidycensus, youre also installing the tigris package. The tigris package has some useful tools that you can use independently of tidycensus. For example, you can use tigris just to download shapefiles without any data assocaited with them. You can also use a function called shift_geometry() when youre making a national map and want Alaska and Hawaii to appear in a layout-friendly location somewhere off the Pacific coast of Mexico.

The example below uses that tigris function and also a package called viridis, which gives you some nice color palletes that people who know say are useful for choropleth maps: https://www.thinkingondata.com/something-about-viridis-library/

#install.packages("viridis")

county_pov <- get_acs(geography = "county",
                      variables = "B17001_002",
                      summary_var = "B17001_001",
                      geometry = TRUE) %>% 
  tigris::shift_geometry() %>%
  mutate(pctpov = 100 * (estimate/summary_est))
## Getting data from the 2016-2020 5-year ACS
## Downloading feature geometry from the Census website.  To cache shapefiles for use in future sessions, set `options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)`.
ggplot(county_pov) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = pctpov), color=NA) +
  coord_sf(datum=NA) +
  labs(title = "Percent of population in poverty by county",
       subtitle = "Alaska and Hawaii are shifted and not to scale",
       caption = "Source: ACS 5-year, 2016",
       fill = "% in poverty") +
  viridis::scale_fill_viridis(direction=-1)

But of course in the real world county borders dont confine the hospital beds that peolpe use. We can get R to show us the density of our hospital points by doing a kernel density estimate for us. Our new function here is ggplot geom called stat_density2d(). More at https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/geom_density_2d.html

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=ncpop, 
          color = "#777777", 
          fill=NA, 
          size=0.2) +
  stat_density2d(data=nc, 
                 show.legend=F, 
                 aes(x=LONGITUDE, 
                     y=LATITUDE, 
                     fill=after_stat(level), 
                     alpha=after_stat(level)
                     ), 
                 geom="polygon", 
                 size=4, 
                 bins=10) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low="deepskyblue2", 
                      high="firebrick1", 
                      name="Distribution") +
  labs(x=NULL, y=NULL, 
                  title="Hospital Coverage in N.C.",
                  subtitle=NULL,
                  caption="Source: US Census, Department of Homeland Security") +
  theme_void() + 
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = 'transparent'))

Part 2: Finding Overlapping Geometries with Hospitals and Congressional Districts

Weve plotted points (hospitals). Weve plotted polygons (counties). Weve plotted the points on top of the polygons. And by using a common value in our points and polygon sf objects, weve joined them together like we would any old other dataframe and then mapped the number of beds in each county.

But what if we wanted to count the number of hospital points inside some OTHER kind of polygon and one for which we dont have a column to join on. For example, we might wonder which voting precinct each hospital is in. Im not sure why wed want to know that, but if we did, we couldnt do it UNLESS we could ask R to tell us which hospitals latitude and longitude points fell within the boundaries of each polygon.

This is called finding the points-in-polygon, and its just one of many different ways we can look for the overlapping relationship between points, lines and polygons on a map.

Finding which hospitals are inside each congressional district is something that might be useful. Maybe because were looking at federal funding levels for healthcare or maybe because were looking at whether some hospitals get some kind of regulatory relief in a loophole created by a certain member of Congress.

We can use tidycensus to get a map of the (pre-2022) congressional districts in R (https://walker-data.com/tidycensus/articles/basic-usage.html#geography-in-tidycensus )

9. Use tidycensus to get the shapes and populations of North Carolinas 13 congressional districts as they existed before the 2020 Census. Go ahead and map them to make sure they look OK.

cds<- get_acs(state = "NC",

So far weve been able to ignore all that projection stuff we were talking about at the start of the lesson. But when we want to ask about the intersection of points, lines and polygons we need to be darn certain that the layers we want to compare are in the same projection.

Luckily,the sf package has a way for us to find the CRS for any sf object. The sf package also has a way for us to change the projection of any sf object. And we can use a new-to-us package called crsuggest to help us determine the best CRS for a given object.

The authory of the tidycensus package has also published a freely available book that provides a good reference for all this CRS stuff: https://walker-data.com/census-r/census-geographic-data-and-applications-in-r.html?q=CRS#coordinate-reference-systems

NAD83 is the CRS that the congressional districts are already in. But is it the best CRS to use? Lets check.

Now we use the wonderful st_join() function from the sf package to do a spatial join. When we do this spatial join, R will tell us for each hospital which congressional district it is in.

The st_join function works similar to a left_join on non-geographic data frames. By default, we are going to keep everything on the left side of the join (the first argument in the function) and we would lose any object on the right side of the join (the second argument in the function) that doesnt fall within any of North Carolinas 13 congressional district polygons. (You can change this default behavior and keep EVERYTHING on both the left and the right by adding a left = F argument inside st_join.)

Reference: https://r-spatial.github.io/sf/reference/st_join.html

points_in <- sf::st_join(cds, nc)

#How do you know we didn't lose any hospitals?

12. Use the points_in object to group all the hospitals by congressional district and then count the number of hospitals in each district.

Hint: We want our new sf object to have three columns one called district that you will create with the group_by(), the second called hospitals which you will create with the summarize(), a third called geometry which will just always exist because its an sf object.

by_cd <- points_in %>%
  group_by(district = NAME.x) %>%
  summarise(hospitals = n())

Building a leaflet map is a little like using ggplot. First you initialize a canvas on which we can paint the map.

Doing so will render you map in the Viewer tab in the RStudio pane that is (probably) to the left.)

my_first_map <- leaflet()

A lot of what were going to do next will look familiar. But were going to do two new things: * Try out a new style of map tiles(https://leaflet-extras.github.io/leaflet-providers/preview/index.html) * Use the addCircles() function from leaflet to map data from our dd_state dataframe.

In this example we use the lon column (which could be named anything) to tell leaflet that this is where it should find the longitude of each markers center point. We then tell it to use the lat column (which could be named anything) to tell leaflet that this is where it should find the latitude of each markers center point. We then tell leaflet to use the text of each rows type column as the text in the popup box. Finally, we set constants for the weight, radius, color, stroke and fillOpacity of the circles we want to draw. But we could also use values in one our dataframes columns to create variable values for any of these circle attributes. For example, we could make the radius of every circle represent the number of MUNCHKINS sold at each location. (Why we need the tildes? Because I said so.)

m2 <- leaflet(dd_state) %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.DarkMatter) %>%
  setView(-79.055847, 35.913200, zoom = 7) %>%
  addCircles(lng=~lon, 
             lat=~lat, 
             popup=dunkin$type, 
             weight = 3, 
             radius=40,
             color="#ffa500", 
             stroke = TRUE, 
             fillOpacity = 0.8)

m2

17. Which congressional districts have the most Starbucks?

Im sure someone has done this at least 15 years ago, but Ill bet theres a correlation between the number of Starbucks in a congressional district and its partisan leanings.

This might sound like a good ol fashioned points-in-polygon analysis. But only one problem our points arent in a sf object at all, nevermind being in the same projection as the polygon layer of congressional districts.

With a little careful work, we can use the st_as_sf() function from the sf package to convert a plain old dataframe into a geographic sf object.

sb_state_sf <- sf::st_as_sf(sb_state,
#Which columns contain the lat and long? Be sure to put them in the 'wrong' order.
                            coords = c("lon","lat"),
#This line just establishes a crs
                            crs = "+proj=longlat") %>%
#Get our data in the same project as the data we want to join
  sf::st_transform(crs=sf::st_crs(cds))

Now that youve got two sf objects with matching crs, go ahead and do a spatial join and then organize the data so you have one row for each congressional district and a column called total that shows the number of Starbucks locations in the district. HINT: Youll have three columns: NAME, locations, geometry.

sbxcd <- sf::st_join(cds, sb_state_sf)
  
sbxcd<- sbxcd %>%
  group_by(NAME) %>%
  summarize(total=n())
# Creating a color palette based on the number range in the total column
pal_sb <- colorNumeric("Greens", domain=sbxcd$total)
# Setting up the pop up text
popup_sb <- paste0("There are ",as.character(sbxcd$total), " Starbucks in ",sbxcd$NAME )
# Getting rid of rows with NA values
# Using the Base R method of filtering subset() because we're dealing with a SpatialPolygonsDataFrame and not a normal data frame, thus filter() wouldn't work

#sbxcd <- subset(sbxcd, !is.na(total))
sbxcd <- sf::st_transform(sbxcd, crs = 4326)


m17 <- leaflet() %>%
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") %>%
  setView(-79.055847, 35.913200, zoom = 7) %>% 
  addPolygons(data = sbxcd , 
              fillColor = ~pal_sb(sbxcd$total), 
              fillOpacity = 0.7, 
              weight = 0.2, 
              smoothFactor = 0.2, 
              popup = ~popup_sb) %>%
  addLegend(pal = pal_sb, 
            values = sbxcd$total, 
            position = "bottomright", 
            title = "Starbucks")

m17
